Sentence: Absence of the clavicles as a developmental defect.
A rounded, bulging chest that resembles the shape of a barrel. That is, there is an increased anteroposterior diameter and usually some degree of kyphosis.
A decreased amount of cystine in the blood.
A benign central bone tumor of the jaw composed of fibrous connective tissue within which bone is formed.
Complete lack of the M photopigment, which is replaced with the L photopigment. Affected individuals tend to confuse red and green.
Additional scrotum, or part of a scrotum in an abnormal location.
Formation of the sacrum bone tissue occurs later than age-adjusted norms.
An abnormality of the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain.
A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.
A type of focal automatism seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
Presence of multiple yellowish-white lesions of various size and configuration on the retina not related to vascular lesions.
A type of strabismus characterized by permanent upward deviation of the visual axis of one eye.

Loss and/or fragmentation of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta creating increasingly extended translamellar spaces, with absence of elastic fibers, and increased gaps in elastic fiber lamellae as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.
A focal behavior arrest seizure characterised by retained awareness throughout the seizure.

Infection of the lungs with Histoplasma capsulatum. Symptoms may include fever, headache, weakness, chest pain and dry cough. When imaging is done, chest radiographs may show patchy pneumonia involving one or more lobes with adenopathy of the mediastinum or hilum.
A focal motor seizure with dystonia characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.
An erosion of the mucous membrane in a portion of the duodenum.
An area of depressed vision located at the point of fixation and that interferes with central vision.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.
A cyst located along the allantois canal.
An abnormal polygonal shape of the calices of the kidney (which normally have a rounded or cup-shaped appearance).
A twisting of the Fallopian tube. Sudden onset with sharp, colicky pelvic pain associated with nausea, vomiting, bowel, and bladder symptoms is the usual presentation.

A less than normal number of sternal ossification centers. The sternum is initially formed from bilateral sternal plates that chondrify and begin to fuse with ribs at 10 weeks gestational age. Ossification starts in the manubrium and upper part of the sternal body at the 6th month, in the middle of the sternal body at the 7th month, in the lower part of the body during the 1st postnatal year and in the xiphoid process between years 5 and 18. The number of ossification centers vary up to six, and it is the ossification centers that are visualized by prenatal ultrasound. This term describes a reduction in the number of ossification centers compared with age-related norms.
Reduced thickness of the outer, dense layer of the myocardium.
A reduced level of the complement component C4b in circulation.
An elevated concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
Blue and green cones only; no functional red cones.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against cow milk protein.
A type of age-related cataract that primarily affects the nucleus of the lens.
An increased amount of cystine in the blood.
An area of the retina that is buckled so that a sector-shaped sheet of retina lies in front of the normal retina. This feature is of congenital onset.
Reduced distance from the anterior border of the naris to the subnasale.
Partial dislocation of the lens in a superior direction.
Midline indentation or cleft of the scrotum.
Drusen (singular, 'druse') are tiny yellow or white accumulations of extracellular material (lipofuscin) that build up in Bruch's membrane of the eye.
Increased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Third-degree atrioventricular (AV) block (also referred to as complete heart block) is the complete dissociation of the atria and the ventricles. Third-degree AV block exists when more P waves than QRS complexes exist and no relationship (no conduction) exists between them.
Decreased amount of leucine in the blood.
A type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by repetitive and rapid saccades, in association with epileptic discharges.
A cataract which affects the layer of the lens surrounding the nucleus, i.e., the lens cortex. It is identified by its unique wedge or spoke appearance.
A reduced circulating concentration of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9.
A narrowing of the vagina owing to scar formation.
The presence of microscopic crystalline calcium precipitates in the form of oxalate and/or phosphate in the renal parenchyma.
An abnormally high level of blood oxygen in the cord blood.
Underdeveloped nails of the fifth toes.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the inferior oblique muscle.
Lack of one or more of the normal pulmonary fissures.
A kind of focal dystonia characterized by forceful contractions of the face, jaw, and/or tongue causing difficulty in opening and closing the mouth and often affecting chewing and speech.
Elongated and tortuous mesenteric veins, which comprise the inferior mesenteric vein and the superior mesenteric vein.
A kind of atrial septum defect arising from an enlarged foramen ovale, inadequate growth of the septum secundum, or excessive absorption of the septum primum.

Os odontoideum is classified into two anatomic types (orthotopic and dystopic). Os odontoideum is defined as an ossicle that consists of smooth and separate caudal portions of the odontoid process. With orthotopic os odontoideum, the ossicle moves with the anterior arch of the atlas, while the dystopic type consists of an ossicle near the basion, or one that is fused with the clivus
Tremor that occurs during any voluntary movement. It may include visually or non-visually guided movements. Tremor during target directed movement is called intention tremor.
An abnormally high concentration of myristoleate in the blood circulation.
Abnormal location of the insertion of a papillary muscle into the left ventricular wall.
A type of focal autonomic seizure characterized by pupillary dilatation or contraction as the initial semiological feature.
A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more vertebrae.

The patient stands with the feet placed together and balance and is asked to close his or her eyes. A loss of balance upon eye closure is a positive Romberg sign and is interpreted as indicating a deficit in proprioception.
A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward.
Polymorphic ventricular arrhythmias of varying morphologythat do not exist under resting conditions but appear only upon physical exercise or catecholamine administration.

An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a low signal on T1-weighted sequences and high signal on T2-weighted sequences. Modic type I changes are thought to represent bone marrow edema and inflammation.
The presence of non-malignant hyperplasia of the prostate.
A type of focal tonic seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
Bilateral clubfoot deformity (see HP:0001762).
A form of latent strabismus (heterophoria) in which the occluded eye wheel-rotates on dissociation.
Prematurely closed sternal sutures.
The length of the incisura from the upper to lower border is greater than that observed in the average population.
An increased amount of arginine levels in the blood.
The presence of a bicuspid pulmonary valve.
Dysplasia of the cervical vertebral column.
The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the main pulmonary artery.
A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze below the horizontal meridian.
Delayed ahcievement of the ability to roll front to back and back to front.
A thickening of the stratum corneum in the region beneath the nails.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the tibia, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
An abnormally elevated concentration od mead acid in the blood circulation.
A type of megaloblastic anemia (i.e., anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal) that improves upon the administration of thiamine.
A decreased amount of phenylalanine in the blood.
Typical absence seizures starting before the age of 4 years.
A predominantly right ventricular variant of isolated noncompaction cardiomyopathy.
Abnormal development of the choroid and retina.
Increased density of the bony tissue of the scapula.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of complex N-glycans on glycoproteins.
An abnormally high concentration of octadecanoate in the blood circulation. Octadecanoate is a fatty acid anion 18:0 that is the conjugate base of octadecanoic acid (stearic acid).
A focal bilateral motor seizure characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.
Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to identify a moving object (typically hand motion at distance of 30 cm).
Severe or complete weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities.
Failure of the foramen ovale to seal postnatally, leaving a potential conduit between the left and right cardiac atria.
A type of dyssynergia affecting eye movements and characterized by the inability to smoothly follow a visual target across the visual field.
A focal cognitive seizure characterized by forced thinking as the initial semiological manifestation.
Congenital absence of the scrotum.
A colon of abnormally small caliber.
Increased susceptibility to infections with Escherichia coli, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection with this agent.

A type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by repeated motor, typically clonic events repeatedly affecting the same segments of the body with spread of clonic movements through contiguous body parts unilaterally, and repeating over a sufficiently prolonged period to reach a diagnosis of status epilepticus.
The presence of a bilobed gallbladder, related to a duplication of the gallbladder primordium.

In otherwise healthy smokers, characteristic so called smoker-inclusion can be found within the macrophages in the bronchoalveolar fluid. These blue/ black/ round/ oval cytoplasmic inclusions consist of pigmented lipid deposits.
Underdevelopment of the helix that either affects the entire helix, or is localized.

Epilepsia partialis continua (also called Kojevnikov's or Kozhevnikov's epilepsia) is a type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by repeated stereotyped simple motor manifestations such as jerks, typically of a limb or the face, recurring every few seconds or minutes for extended periods (days or years).
Failure of attachment of the retina during development.
Elevated concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.

A testis that is located at the upper scrotum or lower inguinal canal and that can be made to descend completely into the scrotum without resistance by manual reduction but returns to its original position by the cremasteric reflex.
A renal cyst characterized by epithelium lined space (squamous/columnar) with septations.
The presence of many cysts in the medulla of the kidney.
An abnormally low level of blood oxygen in the cord blood.
Hypopigmented hair that appears silver-gray.

Subcortical heterotopia extending along the mesial aspect of the lateral ventricles, with direct connection to mesial polymicrogyria-like cortex at the anterior and posterior limits of the heterotopia.
A focal cognitive seizure characterized by dyscalculia / acalculia as the initial semiological manifestation.
A type of focal autonomic seizure characterized by changes of the skin as the initial semiological feature.
Chronic rhinitis accompanied by pus formation.
An decreased concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

A scoliosis which is the results of a difference in leg length (which might be due to hemihypertrophy or hemihypotrophy of a leg) and the resulting tilting of the pelvis. If untreated this will lead to the development of scoliosis over time.
Circumscribed depigmentation of the hair of the head or the eyelashes.
Aplasia of the malleus.
Underdevelopment of the arch of aorta.
EEG dominated by diffuse beta-waves (>13 Hz).
Intermittent clonic or tonic contraction of muscles supplied by facial nerve. Muscles are relaxed in between contractions.

Hyperkeratosis lenticularis perstans (HLP), also known as Flegel disease, is a keratinization abnormality characterized by small, asymptomatic erythematous papules that leave characteristic punctate bleeding when they become detached. The lesions generally occur symmetrically along the top of the foot and on the legs, appearing more rarely on the arms, forearms, palms, and soles, and even on the oral mucosa.
A type of age-related cataract that primarily affects the cortex of the lens.
A hyperpigmented circumscribed area of change in normal skin color without elevation or depression of any size.
Heterotopia that forms a continuous wavy line along the ventricular wall.
Underdevelopment of the vestibular nerve.
Focal emotional seizure with paranoia is characterized by the presence of paranoia as an expressed or observed emotion at the outset of the seizure.

No detectable response to the light-adapted 3.0 ERG (single-flash cone response). This type of ERG measures responses of the cone system; a-waves arise from cone photoreceptors and cone off-bipolar cells; the b-wave comes from On- and Off-cone bipolar cells.
An abnormal indentation of the skin in the region of the nasal tip.

Histoplasmosis infection involving multiple sites of the body. Disseminated histoplasmosis can involve various organs, including reticuloendothelial organs, gastrointestinal tract, adrenal glands, central nervous system, endovascular structures, kidney, and skin. It typically presents with systemic symptoms like fever, generalized fatigue, night sweats, weight loss, and the symptoms related to the specific organ involved. Severe disseminated disease can manifest as septic shock, multi organ failure, and ARDS.

Osteopoikilosis is a benign, asymptomatic sclerotic dysplasia of the bones. It affects both male and female and may be seen at any age. Radiographically sclerotic circular or ovoid lesions are usually symmetrically distributed in a periarticular location. Lesions can increase or decrease in size and number in serial radiographs or even disappear and do not have increased bone radiotracer uptake.

The presence of an aortic valve with two instead of the normal three cusps (flaps). Bicuspid aortic valvue is a malformation of a commissure (small space between the attachment of each cusp to the aortic wall) and the adjacent parts of the two corresponding cusps forming a raphe (the fused area of the two underdeveloped cusps turning into a malformed commissure between both cusps; the raphe is a fibrous ridge that extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps).
Abnormally flat configuration of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.
Increased numbers of plasma cells in the interstitial tissues of the kidney.
Spontaneous pain is a kind of neuropathic pain which occurs without an identifiable trigger.
A decreased amount of lysine in the blood.
Increased pigmentation (skin color) of the scrotum.
A type of myoclonic status epilepticus in the absence of coma.
Reduced ocular movement of the superior oblique muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.
Reduced ocular movement by the inferior oblique muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.
Anomaly of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.
A 'coral-like' pattern of opacity in the lens of the eye. That is, a cataract with an irregular, stellate form.
An anomaly of the ilium ala. This is the large expanded portion of the ilum which bounds the greater pelvis laterally.
The presence of a stenotic, i.e., constricted ureter.
Increased numbers of eosinophils in the interstitial tissues of the kidney.
Any ventricular septal defect (VSD) that is small enough to restrict flow across it such that a pressure gradient exists between the two sides of the VSD.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.
Abnormally increased levels of arginine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Decreased strength of the medial rectus muscle.
An abnormally wavy surface or edge of the ribs.
Nasal ridge curving posteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip.
Nodding movement of the head or body.

Stapes ankylosis refers to congenital or acquired fixation of the stapes (the stirrup-shaped small bone or ossicle in the middle ear), which is associated with conductive hearing resulting from impairment of the sound-conduction mechanism (the external auditory canal, tympanic membrane, and/or middle-ear ossicles).
Increased size of the ridge of tissue that extends along the midline of the scrotum.
Presence of cysts at the corticomedullary junction of the kidney in combination with tubulointerstitial fibrosis.

A congenital malformation in which one or both of the papillary muscles (posteromedial or anterolateral) insert directly (that is, without interpositioned chordae tendineae) into the anterior mitral leaflet.
A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) located between the central point of fixation and the blind spot with a roughly horizontal oval shape.
Generalized-onset tonic-clonic seizures that are provoked by flashing or flickering light.
A rare birth defect in women where the urethra and vagina both open into a common channel.
Insertion of the posterior columella below the nasal base.
Distention of the vagina caused by accumulation of fluid due to congenital vaginal obstruction.
Aplasia of the stapes.
Noncompaction cardiomyopathy that affects both ventricles.
A type of megaloblastic anemia (i.e., anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal) that improves upon the administration of folate.
Reduced length of the clavicles.
A type of dyssynergy characterized by the lack of the ability to smoothly perform the elements of a voluntary movement in the appropriate order and speed.
Posterior malposition of the anus.
Aplasia of the pancreas.
An abnormality of the fovea centralis, the central area of the macula that mediates central, high resolution vision and contains the largest concentration of cone cells in the retina.
A pale yellow discoloration of the optic disk (the area of the optic nerve head in the retina). The optic disc normally has a pinkish hue with a central yellowish depression.
Generalized reduced transparency of the stroma of the cornea.
Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of acylcarnitine, which is produced by reversible esterification of the 3-hydroxyl group of carnitine.
Decrease in width of the nasal tip.
An increased concentration of glutamine in the blood.
Colpocephaly is an anatomic finding in the brain manifested by occipital horns that are disproportionately enlarged in comparison with other parts of the lateral ventricles.
A focal sensory seizure during which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.

Multicystic dysplasia of the kidney is characterized by multiple cysts of varying size in the kidney and the absence of a normal pelvicaliceal system. The condition is associated with ureteral or ureteropelvic atresia, and the affected kidney is nonfunctional.
An abnormality of the normal developmental rotation of the kidney leading to an abnormal axial orientation of the kidney.
Cysts of the cortex of the kidney.
Underdevelopment of the colon.
Urethra more open or expanded than normal.

An abnormal concentration of an HDL subfraction, which can be determined by methods such as electrophoresis followed by densitometric determination of the areas under the peaks. Large HDL subfractions are defined as HDL1 (greater than 12 nm), HDL2b (9.7-12 nm), and HDL2a (8.8-9.69 nm). Small HDL subfractions are defined as HDL3a (8.2-8.79 nm), HDL3b (7.8-8.19 nm), and HDL3c (7.20-7.79 nm).
Absence of one half of the vertebral body.

An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a low signal on T1 and T2-weighted sequences. Modic type III signals are thought to correspond to subchondral sclerosis seen on plain radiographs.

A type of atrial arrhythmia characterized by atrial rates of between 240 and 400 beats per minute and some degree of atrioventricular node conduction block. Typically, the ventricular rate is half the atrial rate. In the EKG; atrial flutter waves are observed as sawtooth-like atrial activity. Pathophysiologically, atrial flutter is a form of atrial reentry in which there is a premature electrical impulse creates a self-propagating circuit.

A varicocele is a widening of the veins along the spermatic cord, leading to enlarged, twisted veins in the scrotum, and manifested clinically by a painless testicle lump, scrotal swelling, or bulge in the scrotum.
A seizure characterized by taste phenomena including acidic, bitter, salty, sweet, or metallic tastes as its first clinical manifestation.
The presence of an abnormal connection between the urethra and another organ or the skin.
Difficulty distinguishing between yellow and blue, possible related to dysfunction of the S photopigment.
An increased number of IgG4+ plasma cells in the interstitial space of the kidney.
Accumulation of inhaled, nondigestable particles in macrophages.
Atrophy of the optic nerve. Optic atrophy results from the death of the retinal ganglion cell axons that comprise the optic nerve and manifesting as a pale optic nerve on fundoscopy.
An abnormal decrease in the concentration of monosialylated core 1 O-glycans on glycoproteins.
Rupture of the wall of the gallbladder.
A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the duodenal lumen, that is, an abnormal closure of the duodenum.
A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies.
Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium occuring near the outer limit (periphery) of the retina.
Nasal tip positioned to one side of the midline.
Episodes of choreoathetosis that can occur following triggers such as quick voluntary movements.

Paralysis of all four limbs, and trunk of the body below the level of an associated injury to the spinal cord. The etiology of quadriplegia is similar to that of paraplegia except that the lesion is in the cervical spinal cord rather than in the thoracic or lumbar segments of the spinal cord.
Underdevelopment of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.
Abnormality of macular or foveal pigmentation.
Schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.
Absence of the scapulae.
Absence of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.

An ostium primum atrial septal defect is located in the most anterior and inferior aspect of the atrial septum. The ostium primum refers to an anterior and inferior opening (ostium) within the septum primum, which divides the rudimentary atrium during fetal development. The ostium primum is normally sealed by fusion of the superior and inferior endocardial cushions around 5 weeks' gestation. Ostium primum defects result from a failure of the fusion of the embryologic endocardial cushion and septum primum.
A type of myoclonic status epilepticus in the presence of coma.
An abnormally increased potassium concentration in the blood.
A focal sensory seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the forehead.

Ichthyosis follicularis is characterized by widespread non inflammatory thorn-like follicular projections. Dyskeratotic papules are most pronounced over the extensor extremities and scalp and are symmetrically distributed.

Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium, i.e., localized or generalized fundal pigment granularity associated with processes at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium.
Paralysis (complete loss of muscle function) in the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.
Weakness of the cartilage in the trachea and the bronchi, resulting in a floppy (non-rigid) airway. Affected persons may have difficulties to maintain patency of the airways.
Yellow, white or greyish lesions in the retina that are well-defined/distinct, individual and mostly uniform in size.

Any anomaly of the ring of fibrous tissue that surrounds the optic nerve at its entrance at the apex of the orbit. The common tendinous ring, also known as the annulus of Zinn or annular tendon, is the origin for five of the seven extraocular muscles.

Infiltration of eosinophils in the stomach mucosa, that is diagnosed by an upper endoscopy and microscopy that shows more than 20 eosinophils per high-power field in association with peripheral eosinophilia and the absence of secondary cause of eosinophilia.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of core 1 O-glycans on glycoproteins.

Pseudocoarctation is a congenital anomaly of kinking, or buckling, of the aorta without a pressure gradient across the lesion. It is characterized by elongation and kinking of the aorta at the level of the ligamentum arteriosum.
Decreased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.
Irregularity of the iliac crest, which is the superior border of the wing of the ilium.
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting head movement.
An increased concentration of valine in the blood.
EEG dominated by diffuse alpha-waves (8-13Hz).
A sensation consistent with involvement of the autonomic nervous system, including cardiovascular, gastrointestinal, sudomotor, vasomotor and thermoregulatory functions.
An abnormality of the eyelids.
The presence of a supernumerary, i.e. third, crus of the helix in the helix, arising at or above the normal bifurcation of the antihelix.
An isometric tremor occurs with muscle contraction against a rigid stationary object (e.g., when making a fist).
Accumulation of clear fluid in the between the layers of membrane (tunica vaginalis) surrounding the testis.
Focal emotional seizure with anger is characterized by the presence of anger, as an expressed or observed emotion, at the outset of the seizure. It may be accompanied by aggressive behaviour.
Bilateral absence (atresia) of the posterior nasal aperture (choana).
Two clitorides located side by side.
Abnormally increased levels of glycine in cerebrospinal fluid.
The presence of birefringent calcium- and oxalate deposits in interstitial cells of the kidney.
Inability to develop or maintain an erection of the penis.
Underdevelopment of the optic disc, that is of the optic nerve head, where ganglion cell axons exit the eye to form the optic nerve.
A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone can be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the external carotid artery wall.
Positioning of the nasal tip inferior to the nasal base.
A generalized decrease in bone mineral density.
A ventricular septal defect that is confluent with and involves the membranous septum and is bordered by an atrioventricular valve, not including the type 3 VSDs.
EEG background activity at 4-5/second.
Breadth of the incisura from the anterior to posterior border greater than that observed in the average population.
Affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual auras with subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognized by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.
Reduced concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.
A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries.
An abnormality of the cerebral cortex.

Focal emotional seizure with anxiety is characterized by the presence of anxiety, fear or panic as an expressed or observed emotion, at the outset of the seizure. Because of the unpleasant nature of these seizures, patients may also have anticipatory anxiety about having seizures.
Abnormally decreased levels of alanine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Sclerosis (abnormal hardening) of cortical bone, characterized by increased radiodensity.
Presence of a many diverticula (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.
Dysfunction of the proximal tubule, which is the portion of the duct system of the nephron of the kidney which leads from Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle.
Excessive action of the lateral rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.
A type of cataract affecting the anterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the lens capsule.
A focal motor seizure with version characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the superior mesenteric artery .
Width of the incisura from the anterior to posterior border less than that observed in the average population.
Increased inferior to superior extent of the thorax.
A shift from the normally round (convex) appearance of the iliac wing towards a square-like appearance.
An increased number and density of the trabeculae in the apex (tip) of the left ventricle.
A ventricular septal defect that lies beneath the semilunar valve(s) in the conal or outlet septum.
A duplication of the renal pelvis.
An abnormally high concentration of oleic acid (oleate) in the blood circulation.
Superior margin of the scrotum superior to the base of the penis.

A nuclear cataract is an opacity or clouding that develops in the lens nucleus. That is, a nuclear cataract is one that is located in the center of the lens. The nucleus tends to darken changing from clear to yellow and sometimes brown.
Multiple defects in the atrial septum.
Excessive action of the inferior rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
Tendency for the visual axis of one eye to be higher than that of the other.
A focal autonomic seizure characterised by retained awareness throughout the seizure.
The enteric villi are atrophic or absent.
An increase in size of the subarachnoid space associated with the lateral cerebral sulcus (Sylvian fissure).
A thumbnail that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped thumb nail.
Meckel's diverticulum is a congenital diverticulum located in the distal ileum.
A groove of the skin immediately in front of the ear.
The presence of an aortic valve with four instead of the normal three cusps (flaps).
Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the uterus.
Abnormally decreased levels of glutamic acid in cerebrospinal fluid.
Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Knee clonus can be tested by rapidly pushing the patella towards the toes.
A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.
A developmental defect resulting in abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the jejunum.
A type of focal clonic seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking rapidly involves one side of the body at seizure onset.

An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a high signal on T1-weighted sequences and high- or isointense signal on T2 sequences. Modic type II signals are thought to indicate fatty replacement in the bone marrow.
An abnormal accentuation of the inward curvature of the spine in the lumbar region.
Diffuse, bilateral and recently also unilateral or focal localization spike-wave occurring in slow sleep or non-rapid eye movement sleep.
A form of manifest strabismus (heterotropia) in which the one eye is wheel rotated so that the upper end of its vertical axis is nasal (incyclotropia) or temporal (excyclotropia).

Patchy or diffuse ischemic destruction of all the elements of renal cortex resulting from significantly diminished renal arterial perfusion. Coagulative necrosis may be present, involving all tubular segments and glomeruli. Nuclei may be pale and pyknotic, or may no longer be apparent. Thrombi may be present in vessels at the edge of the infarct.
Abnormally increased levels of aspartic acid in cerebrospinal fluid.
Increased width of the columella.
Increased concentration of dopamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone cannot be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone or similar glucocorticoids.
Peripheral arterial stenosis with onset before the age of 50 years.

A congenital variant of a coronary artery in which a portion of an epicardial coronary artery (most frequently the middle segment of the left anterior descending artery) takes an intramuscular course.
Congenital absence of the colon
Crystalline deposits in the retina.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the common carotid artery wall.
Supernumerary clitoris.
One or both of the leaflets (cusps) of the mitral valve bulges back into the left atrium upon contraction of the left ventricle.
Decreased posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.
Increased side-to-side width of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

Increase in size of the cisterna magna, one of three principal openings in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid and pia mater, located between the cerebellum and the dorsal surface of the medulla oblongata.
Aplasia (congenital absence) of the vas deferens.

Lack of observable abnormal electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns in an individual with a history of seizures. About half of individuals with epilepsy show interictal epileptiform discharges upon the first investigation. The yield can be increased by repeated studies, sleep studies, or by ambulatory EEG recordings over 24 hours. Normal interictal EEG is a sign that can be useful in the differential diagnosis.
Absence or abnormal closure of the posterior portion of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
An increased concentration of alanine in the blood.
A focal aware cognitive seizure during which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.
Generalised myoclonic seizure provoked by flashing or flickering light.

A type of retinal detachment arising from damage to the outer blood-retinal barrier that allows fluid to access the subretinal space and separate the neurosensory retina from the retinal pigment epithelium.
A developmental defect characterized by absence of the retina.

A focal cognitive seizure characterized by auditory agnosia as the initial semiological manifestation. For example a person may hear a ringing sound, but may not connect this with the concept that the sound is from a telephone ringing.
An abnormality of the cerebral subcortex.
A cataract which is found in the back outer layer of the lens. This type often develops more rapidly.
Abnormally increased sensitivity to pain.
A motility disorder characterized by biliary colic in the absence of gallstones with a reduced gallbladder ejection fraction.
Decreased width of the foramen obturatorium. The foramen obturatorium (also known as the obturator foramen) is a hole located between the ischium and pubis bones of the pelvis.

Unroofed coronary sinus (CS) is a rare congenital cardiac anomaly in which there is partial (either focal or fenestrated) or complete absence of the roof of the CS, which results in a communication between the CS and the LA. Unroofed CS is the rarest type of atrial septal defect. It is often associated with persistent left superior vena cava (LSVC) and other forms of complex congenital heart disease, usually heterotaxia syndromes. The morphological types have been classified into 4 groups: Type I, completely unroofed with persistent LSVC; type II, completely unroofed without persistent LSVC; type III, partially unroofed mid portion; and type IV, partially unroofed terminal portion.
Reduction of the diameter of the coronary arteries as the result of an accumulation of atheromatous plaques within the walls of the coronary arteries, which increases the risk of myocardial ischemia.
The presence of calcium-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
Macular dystrophy is a nonspecific term for premature retinal cell aging and cell death, generally confied to the macula in which no clear extrinsic cause is evident.
A severe form of gait ataxia such that an affected person cannot walk at all.
An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood.
Swelling (edema) of the retinal nerve fibers.
Any abnormality of the palate, i.e., of roof of the mouth.
Increased addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
Small defect of the helical fold that lies at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.
A type of ventricular tachycardia that is characterized by uniform QRS complexes within each lead (i.e., each QRS is identical or nearly so).
A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the rectum. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the rectum.
A developmental defect characterized by the absence of the Third ventricle.
Abnormal accumulation of a metabolite, protein, or protein-derived substance in the interstitial region of the kidney.
A form of sensorineural deafness with either congenital onset or infantile onset, i.e., before the acquisition of speech.
Complete lack of functioning of the vestibular apparatus.
Fibrosis of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position. Residual eye movements are significantly limited.
The presence of a single coronary artery ostium from which both coronary arteries arise.
Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the eyelid.
The presence of recurrent corneal epithelial erosions. Although most corneal epithelial defects heal quickly, some may show recurrent ulcerations.

An abnormality of the retina characterized by pigment deposition. It is typically associated with migration and proliferation of macrophages or retinal pigment epithelial cells into the retina; melanin from these cells causes the pigmentary changes. Pigmentary retinopathy is a common final pathway of many retinal conditions and is often associated with visual loss.
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the hand.
A chronic form of gastritis.
Bowing (bulging out) of the muscular part of the interventricular septum of more than 10-15 mm into the cavity of an adjacent ventricle (usually into the right ventricle).
Decreased addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
Habitual striking of one's own head against a surface such as a mattress or wall of a crib.
Decreased distance from the nasal tip to the nasal base.
A type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by prolonged ictal paresis or inhibitory motor seizures.
Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital regions during photic stimulation.
A morphological abnormality of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.

Any anomolous structure of the renal corpuscle, which is the initial component of the nephron that filters blood. The renal corpuscle consists of a knot of capillaries (glomerulus) that is surrounded by a double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.
A form of monochromacy in which vision is derived from the remaining preserved blue (S) cones and rod photoreceptors.
A condition in which the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal. That is, excessive curling of the helix edge, whereby the free edge is parallel to the plane of the ear.
The presence of steatosis in the liver.
The superior vena cava passes below the aortic arch.
Involuntary protrusions, movements, spams and contortions of the tongue.
A symmetric and progressive loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.
Abnormally decreased levels of threonine in cerebrospinal fluid.

Increased plasma concentrations of chylomicrons, the large lipid droplet (up to 100 mm in diameter) of reprocessed lipid synthesized in epithelial cells of the small intestine and containing triacylglycerols, cholesterol esters, and several apolipoproteins.
Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with a smooth appearance of the interlobular septa.
An increased amount of asparagine in the blood.
A morphological abnormality of the metencephalon.
Paroxysmal episodes of vertigo.
A type of cataract affecting the posterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the Lens capsule.

Nonprogressive restriction of movement of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position. Residual eye movements are significantly limited.
Multifocal slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Repeated episodes of a localized, painful cutaneous eruption related to reactivation of varicella zoster virus (VZV) and characterized by a characteristic rash in one or two adjacent dermatomes.
Occurence of epileptiform discharges in occipital and central regions during photic stimulation.
Wasting or decrease in size of all or part of the duodenum.

Any deivation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a thromboxane. Thromboxanes are derived from prostaglandin precursors in platelets, and stimulate aggregation of platelets and constriction of blood vessels.
Abnormally decreased levels of isoleucine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Underdevelopment of the vertebral artery on one side.
Excessive production of saliva.
An abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the ileum.
Persistence of the urachal canal resulting in a canal between the bladder and the umbilicus.
A painful and harmful medical condition in which the erect penis doesn't return to its flaccid state, despite the absence of both physical and psychological stimulation, within four hours.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the inferior mesenteric artery .
An increased amount of aspartic acid in the blood.
Abnormally increased levels of lysine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Reduced transparency of the peripheral region of the cornea.
Abnormally decreased levels of leucine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial avium complex infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.

An atrial arrhythmia characterized by disorganized atrial activity without discrete P waves on the surface EKG, but instead by an undulating baseline or more sharply circumscribed atrial deflections of varying amplitude an frequency ranging from 350 to 600 per minute.
Increased volume and globular shape of the anteroinferior aspect of the nose.
Increased pigmentation of the skin with a netlike (reticular) pattern.
A seizure characterized by a sensation in the head such as light-headedness or headache as its first clinical manifestation.

CT finding of central ground-glass opacity surrounded by denser consolidation of crescentic shape (forming more than three-fourths of a circle) or complete ring of at least 2 mm in thicknes. A rare sign, it was initially reported to be specific for cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, but was subsequently described in patients with paracoccidioidomycosis.
A type of congenital cataract in which the opacity follows the anterior or posterior Y suture.
Absence of fleshy non-cartilaginous tissue inferior to the tragus and incisura.
An increased concentration of hydroxyproline in the blood.
Any structural anomaly of the hypothalamus.
Supraventricular tachycardia in which an accessory pathway connecting the atria and ventricles, apart from the AV node, participates as a necessary part of a reentrant mechanism.

In primary position, the eyes drift slowly downward and then spontaneously beat upward. Upward gaze accentuates the nystagmus. The associated oscillopsias are often very irritating, but the symptoms are usually transient.
Overgrowth of the choroid plexus.

A dementia associated with degeneration of the frontotemporal lobe and clinically associated with personality and behavioral changes such as disinhibition, apathy, and lack of insight. The hallmark feature of frontotemporal dementia is the presentation with focal syndromes such as progressive language dysfunction, or aphasia, or behavioral changes characteristic of frontal lobe disorders.
An abnormal shape of the vertebral bodies whereby the vertebral bodies are thick on one side and taper to a thin edge at the other.

An increase of medial mucoid extracellular matrix creating translamellar and/or intralamellar expansions including extracellular pools as noted on an H&E stain and/or a stain to highlight extracellular matrix material (Movat's pentachrome, Alcian blue, etc.).
A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.
An abnormal generalized reduction in amplitude of the cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
A type of focal atonic seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
Acute renal failure with resolution of manifestations.

Accumulation of foam cells (FC) in the interstitium of the kidney. Renal FCs display phenotypic characteristics of macrophages and belong to the monocyte/macrophage lineage. Histologically, renal FCs are characterized by round cells with small nuclei and an abundant PAS-positive cytoplasm with lipid-containing vacuoles.
A partial or complete breakage of the left clavicle.
A form of ventricular preexcitation due to the presence of multiple accessory pathways for cardiac conduction.
An elevated plasma concentration of sarcosine.

A focal cognitive seizure characterized by transient memory impairment as the initial semiological manifestation whilst other cognitive functions and awareness are preserved at seizure onset. The memory impairment may be an inability to recall events occurring prior to the seizure (retrograde amnesia), or failure to encode new memories for events occurring during the seizure (anterograde amnesia).
A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.
Small, hard cyst-like nodules, freely moveable in the subcutis over the bony prominences of the legs and arms, which have an outer calcified layer with a translucent core on x-ray.
Increased width of the nasal ridge.

A febrile seizure that has any of the following features: focal semiology (or associated with post-ictal neurologic abnormalities beyond drowsiness, such as a Todd's paresis), prolonged seizure beyond 15 minutes, or recurring (occurring more than once) in a 24 hour period.
A type of supraventricular tachycardia that originates in the atrioventricular node.
Greater than normal amounts of fat in the feces. This is a result of malabsorption of lipids in the small intestine and results in frothy foul-smelling fecal matter that floats.
Absence (aplasia) of the sacrum.
An elevation above the normal concentration of manganese in the blood.
Insertion of the posterior columella superior to the nasal base.
Yellow-colored streaks, patches, or spots on the intimal surface of arteries. Fatty streaks stain red with Sudan III or Sudan IV.
A type of focal autonomic seizure characterized by changes in respiratory rate as the initial semiological feature.
A type of dysmetria involving the limbs.

The presence of aneurysmal polypoidal lesions in the choroidal vasculature. The aneurysmal dilatations, also known as polyps, may be found at subfoveal, juxtafoveal, extrafoveal, peripapillary or even peripheral regions. These polypoidal dilatations may be visible as reddish-orange subretinal nodules during ophthalmoscopic examination. The polypoidal lesions are best detected on indocyanine green angiography (ICGA) and might be associated with a branching vascular network (BVN) of neovascularization.
Testicular torsion is when the spermatic cord to a testicle twists, cutting off the blood supply. The most common symptom is acute testicular pain.

Anteriorly-facing nostrils viewed with the head in the Frankfurt horizontal and the eyes of the observer level with the eyes of the subject. This gives the appearance of an upturned nose (upturned nasal tip).
An increased amount of glutamate in the blood.
Fever that occurs at daily intervals.
Abnormally decreased levels of lysine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A partial or complete breakage of the epiphysis.
Formation of excess connective tissue in the testicle.
A sectoral indentation of the crystalline lens, usually due to zonular weakness or absence.
Cystic, urine-containing intrarenal cavities lined with transitional cell epithelium that communicate through a narrow channel with the collecting system.
The presence of more than 12 rib pairs.

The vestibulo-ocular reflex is responsible for the stabilization of the retinal image during movement. The visual vestibular ocular reflex (VVOR) or visual enhanced VOR, maintains ocular stability during head motion by generating compensatory eye movement opposite to head movement, and is a major component of visual vestibular interaction. This feature is an impairment of this reflex, manifested as the combined impairment of the three compensatory eye movement reflexes, namely the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR), smooth pursuit (SP) and optokinetic reflex (OKR).
Abnormally decreased levels of phenylalanine in cerebrospinal fluid.

Focal emotional seizure with pleasure is characterized by the presence of a positive emotional experience with pleasure, bliss, joy, enhanced personal well-being, heightened self-awareness or ecstasy.
Electron-dense granules within double membrane-bound cytoplasmic vacuoles.

A short generalized seizure, of a duration of <15 min, not recurring within 24 h, occurring during a febrile episode not caused by an acute disease of the nervous system intracranial infection or severe metabolic disturbance.
The presence of both a left and a right ductus arteriosus.

An increase in collagen fibers creating areas of substitutive fibrosis or a widening of intralamellar spaces in the media of the aorta. This can be seen in conjunction with a loss to varying degrees of parallel arrangement of the elastic lamellae (or lamellar units).
Cellular infiltrate confirmed by a cellular infiltrate comprised of mainly eosinophils in the gallbladder wall on histological examination.

Thin-cap fibroatheroma is characterized by a relatively large necrotic core with an overlying thin fibrous cap measuring <65 m typically containing numerous macrophages, and is considered to be the precursor lesion of plaque rupture which is the most common cause of coronary thrombosis.

A condition of not having consistently high levels of phenylalanine in the blood but of experiencing temporary hyperphenylalaninemia following ingestion of large quantities of phenylalanine (for instance, following an oral loading test with phenylalanine).
An abnormality of the thalamus.
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the tongue.

An arachnoid cyst that progressively enlarges from an abnormality in the membrane of Liliequist or in the interpeduncular cistern, and typically, expands from the prepontine space, displacing the floor of the third ventricle upwards, the pituitary stalk and optic chiasm upwards and forwards, and the mammillary bodies upwards and backwards.
A focal cognitive seizure characterized by receptive dysphasia / aphasia as the initial semiological manifestation.

Any anomaly of the costochondral junction. The costochondral junctions are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.
Any impairment of reabsorption of chloride by the kidney in order to not lose too much chloride in the urine.
A thickening of the stratum corneum, the outer layer of the skin, in the region surrounding the nails.
An abnormal rise in the volume of water filtered out of plasma through glomerular capillary walls into Bowman's capsules per unit of time.
A fracture of the vertebra that is caused by a loss of bone mass (osteoporosis) that occurs as part of aging.
A type of focal autonomic seizure characterised by symptoms or signs pertaining to the gastrointestinal system as the initial semiological feature.
The practice of eating earth or soil-like substrates such as clay or chalk.
A region of the aortic media in which smooth muscle cell nuclei, involving multiple lamellae, are not clearly identifiable on an hematoxylin and eosin stain.
The combination of pendular nystagmus, head nodding, and torticollis.
A focal hyperkinetic seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

A tremor-like cortical myoclonus. The tremulous movements are in fact small, high-frequency myoclonic jerks, induced by posture or action. They can be mild, but can also be more incapacitating. When present in the lower limbs, these may lead to gait disorders and even drop attacks. These tremor-like movements during action can be mistaken for essential tremor or epileptic seizures.

Fluffy white patch on the retina, representing localized areas of dense white swelling of the retinal nerve fibre layer. They often have a zigzag internal structure, a feathered edge but an otherwise well-delineated form and an approximately 1 mm dimension; they project slightly into the vitreous and sometimes deflect retinal vessels.
Absent nail of big toe.
Agenesis, that is, failure of the kidney to develop during embryogenesis and development.
Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with a nodular or beaded appearance of the interlobular septa.
This term applies if the Epiglottis is absent or hypoplastic.
Abnormally increased levels of threonine in cerebrospinal fluid.
The congenital absence of the sternum.
Reduced volume of the earlobe.
A focal cognitive seizure characterized by dysgraphia / agraphia as the initial semiological manifestation.
An increased consentration of zinc in the blood.
A phenomenon in which persons repetitively pull out their own hair, resulting in noticeable hair loss.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a prostaglandin in the blood circulation.
A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.
An increased amount of tryptophan in the blood.
Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital, central, temporal and parietal regions during photic stimulation.
Excessive action of the superior rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
Abnormally increased levels of tyrosine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Increased width of the alveolar ridges.
Focal emotional seizure with anger in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the anterior chest.
A focal hemiclonic seizure in which awareness is retained throughout.
A type of focal sensory seizure with auditory features during which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.
A focal sensory seizure with cephalic sensation in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
Underdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.
Over curvature of the lower thoracic region, leading to a round back or if sever to a hump.
A focal type of palmoplantar keratoderma in which only certain areas of the palms and soles are affected.
Any abnormality of the sublingual glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth anterior to the submandibular glands.
An abnormality of the appearance of the face caused by constant contraction of the lips leading to a puckered or pursed appearance.
A row of beadlike prominences at the junction of a rib and its cartilage (i.e., enlarged costochondral joints), resembling a rosary.
A below normal level of saturation of serum transferrin with iron.
A type of third degree heart block in which the escape rhythm arises at the atrioventricular node, which produces a narrow QRS complex.
A variant of retinitis pigmentosa in which there is a regional distribution of the retinal degeneration.

An epiretinal membrane is a thin sheet of fibrous tissue that can develop on the surface of the macular area of the retina and cause a disturbance in vision. An epiretinal membrane area can develop on the thin macular area of the retin. An epiretinal membrane is also sometimes called a macular pucker, premacular fibrosis, surface wrinkling retinopathy or cellophane maculopathy.
Sperm cells lacking flagella.
The presence of foam cells that contain lamellar inclusion bodies.
Any structural anomaly of the acrosome resulting in a round sperm head.
Fusion of the labia minora as a result of labial adhesions resulting in vaginal obstruction.

An organized collection of histiocytes (specifically macrophages) localized in the interstitial tissue of the kidney. Through light microscopy, the activated histiocytes appear as epithelioid cells with round to oval nuclei, often with irregular contours and abundant granular eosinophilic cytoplasm with indistinct cell borders. They may also coalesce to form multinucleated giant cells. Granulomas may be associated with a peripheral cuff of lymphoplasmacytic and occcasionally eosinophilic inflammation. Organization can range from poorly-to-well defined. Granulomas can present as necrotizing or non-necrotizing. Microscopically, necrotizing granulomas distinctly have central necrosis with a palisaded lymphohistiocytic reaction and a cuff of chronic inflammation.

Cervical dysplasia is the precursor to cervical cancer. It is caused by the persistent infection of the human papillomavirus (HPV) into the cervical tissue. Affected cells develop morphologic features with immature basaloid- type squamous cells and mitotic figures in the upper half of the cervical epithelium.
The closed form of spina bifida with incomplete closure of a vertebral body with intact overlying skin.
A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance beween the vertebral endplates affecting the lumbar spine.
An abnormality of canine tooth.
Presence of a bifid sacral bone.
A condition in which the superior portion of the helix is folded over to a lesser degree than normal.

IWith incomplete partition II, the cochlea consists of 1.5 turns; the apical and middle cochlea turns are undifferentiated and form a cystic apex. The vestibule is normal while the vestibular aqueduct is always enlarged. Developmental arrest occurs at the seventh week of gestation.
Focal emotional seizure with laughing in which awareness is retained throughout.

A lesion that is observed following light damage to the macula. Damage to the retinal by exposure to intense visible light, usually the sun. Intense light exposure such as staring at the sun causes fine structural anomalies in the outer segments of the photoreceptors and the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) cells of the macula. Symptoms usually develop within 1 to 4 h after exposure and include decreased vision, metamorphopsia, micropsia, and central or paracentral scotomas. Fundus examination typically shows a small yellow spot with a surrounding gray zone in the foveolar or parafoveolar area. Spontaneous evolution leads to the improvement of visual acuity.
A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by the production of single or repetitive words, phrases, or brief sentences at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
Increased size of the head of sperm.
A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more cervical vertebral bodies with one another.
Bony fusion of the posterior part of the L5 vertebral body with the sacrum.
A developmental defect characterized by fusion of the left and right halves of the thalamus.
Transient episodes of weakness of the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.
A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus.
A type of vertical phoria in which, in dissociation, the occluded eye deviates upwards.
An autonomic seizure with palpitations / tachycardia / bradycardia / asystole characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.
Undescended or ectopic ovaries are characterized by the attachment of the upper pole of the ovary to an area above the level of the common iliac vessels.
Slowing in occipital areas of the scalp EEG.

A type of bicuspid aortic valvue (BAV) characterized by the presence of a single raphe that extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps, resulting in two leaflets of unequal size.
A type of cyclotropia (torsion of one or both eye around the visual axis of the eyes) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated inward (medially) to each other.
Fibrous band between the mucosal surfaces of the upper and lower alveolar ridges.
An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood occurring periodically with a return to normal between the episodes.

White lesions of the oral mucosa are generally caused by a condition that increases the thickness of the epithelium. This increases the distance to the vascular bed and thereby tends to change the usual reddish color of the oral mucosa to white. Common causes include hyperkeratosis (thickening of the keratin layer), acanthosis (thickening of the spinous cell layer), increased edema in the epithelium (leukoedema), and reduced vascularity of the underlying lamina propria. Additionally, fibrin caps or surface ulcerations and collapsed bullae can appear white.

A double outlet right ventricle with a non-committed ventricular septal defect (VSD), which is a VSD that is anatomically related to, or close to, neither great vessel, being separated from both by considerable muscle, and also has a pulmonary stenosis; abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

A type of low sperm count where ejaculated semen contains less than 100,000 spermatozoa per ml. With cryptozoospermia, the sperm count may fluctuate and a zero sperm count in the ejaculate may be initially measured. If sperm are observed in a second semen sample following centrifugation, the diagnosis of cryptozoospermia can be made (and azoospermia can be ruled out).
A focal autonomic seizure with erection characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.
Histopathological findings of inflammation of the interstitium of the renal medulla, composed of lymphocytes, monocytes, plasma cells.
A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary head nodding at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth.
A form of esotropia (convergent deviation of the eyes) associated with activation of the accommodative reflex.
An increased rate of urine production.
Swelling related to fluid accumulation within the palate.
The presence of a triangular form of the mouth.
The presence of distinct colors in the central (pupillary) zone of the iris than in the mid-peripheral (ciliary) zone.

Interstital aggregates of histiciocytes, occasionally multinucleated with associated lymphoplasmacytic and occcasionally eosinophilic inflammation. Organization can range from poorly-to-well defined and multinucleated giant cells may be present with no necrosis.

A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by two equal-sized cusps, with no raphe and only two commissures. There is a lateral arrangement of the free edge of the cusps. Note that this differs from some other forms of BAV in which there are three commissures and two of the three cusps are joined by a raphe forming two functional leaflets. This type of BAV often is associated with aortic stenosis.
A type of vertical tropia in which, when one eye is fixing, the other eye is deviated downwards.

A retinopathy with a 50% likelihood of progressing to retinal detachment. Threshold disease is considered to be present when stage 3 retinopathy of prematurity (ROP) is present in either zone I or zone II, with at least 5 continuous or 8 total clock hours of disease, and the presence of plus disease.
A structural anomaly of the glomerulus.
Damage to and obliteration of intrahepatic bile ducts (bile ducts that transport bile between the Canals of Hering and the interlobar bile ducts).
Developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.
A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more thoracic vertebral bodies with one another.
Tremor of the trunk in an anterior-posterior plane at 3-4 Hz.
A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall
Abnormally short chordae tendineae of the mitral valve.
Cervical ectropion occurs when eversion of the endocervix exposes columnar epithelium to the vaginal milieu

A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
A structural anomaly of the double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.
The outer labia are sealed together.
A focal sensory seizure with vestibular features in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
A type of microtropia with no manifest movement on cover test, the eccentric fixation point coinciding with the angle of ARC.
Retinopathy which extends centrifugally from the edge of zone I to the nasal ora serrata.

The commonest form of tetralogy of Fallot characterized by pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy, without pulmonary atresia, absent pulmonary valve, atrioventricular canal defect or absent subarterial conus.
One sided hypoplasia of the kidney.

Junctional ectopic tachycardia (JET) is a unique type of supraventricular arrhythmia defined by narrow QRS complex and atrioventricular (AV) dissociation or retrograde atrial conduction in a 1:1 pattern.

Three ossification sites are present in typical vertebral bodies (C3-L5): a single ossification center in the vertebral body, and one each in the two neural arches. This term applies if there are additional vertebral ossification centers present during the development and maturation of the spine.
Any abnormality of the submandibular glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth, superior to the digastric muscles.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic arch.

A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

Cerulean cataracts are a kind of congenital cataract having peripheral bluish and white opacifications in concentric layers with occasional central lesions arranged radially. Although the opacities may be observed during fetal development and childhood, usually visual acuity is only mildly reduced until adulthood, when lens extraction is generally necessary.
Opacity of the entire lens nucleus.
Failure of formation of the lumen of the gallbladder, often associated with gallbladder hypoplasia.
An abnormal narrowing of the urethral opening (meatus) of the penis.
Bleeding in the thalamus.
A type of microtropia in which the manifest movement is demonstrated on the cover-uncover test.
A seizure characterized by sensations of feeling hot and then cold.
A congenital malformation with abnormal connection between one of the coronary arteries and the pulmonary artery.
Focal emotional seizure with pleasure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
A form of stapes ankylosis with congenital onset.
A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more lumbar vertebral bodies with one another.
An abnormality of molar tooth.

If the two laminae of the septum pellucidum are not fused then a fluid-filled space or cavum is present. The cavum septum pellucidum is present at birth but usually obliterates by the age of 3 to 6 months. It is up to 1cm in width and the walls are parallel. It is an enclosed space and is not part of the ventricular system or connected with the subarachnoid space.
Gallstones composed primarily of cholesterol, usually about 2-3 cm in length with an oval form and a yellow or green/brown color.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of the HDL2a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL2B particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 9.7-12 nm.
An abnormal anatomic position of the fovea, the small, central pit composed of closely packed cones that is located in the macula of the retina.
Lamellar cataracts with associated linear lens opacities radially extending towards the periphery of the lens.

Focal emotional seizure with anxiety, fear or panic as an expressed or observed emotion at the outset of the seizure, in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
An abnormality of the pigmentation of the mucosa of the mouth.
EEG discharges recorded on the entire scalp typically seen in persons with epilepsy.

A type of subvalvular aortic stenosis resulting from thickening of the musculature of the interventricular septum, which results in obstruction to blood flow through the left-ventricular outflow tract.
Congenital deep dermal melanosis in the sacral area.
An inflammation of the ovary or ovaries.

Accumulation of an immunoglobulin in the interstitial tissue of the kidney. The immunoglobulin may be a monoclonal Ig or the corresponding heavy-chain (HC) or light-chain (LC) subunit. By convention this definition excludes Ig-derived amyloidosis (amyloidosis can be distinguished by its affinity for Congo red staining).
Funnel detachment from the retina with generally traction in all four quadrants.
Height of the palate more than 2 SD above the mean (objective) or palatal height at the level of the first permanent molar more than twice the height of the teeth (subjective).
Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized distal to the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the postductal region of aortic arch.

A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Abnormal structure of the basement membrane of the renal tubulus.
A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance beween the vertebral endplates affecting the thoracic spine.
Cerebral eosinophilic, discrete, intracytoplasmatic inclusions of unknown significance.
A type of sutural cataract in which the opacity follows the posterior Y suture.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the tubular part of the ascending aorta.
An abnormality of the upper lip.

Type V lesions are defined as lesions in which prominent new fibrous connective tissue has formed. When the new tissue is part of a lesion with a lipid core (type IV), this type of morphology may be referred to as fibroatheroma or type Va lesion. A type V lesion in which the lipid core and other parts of the lesion are calcified may be referred to as type Vb. A type V lesion in which a lipid core is absent and lipid in general is minimal may be referred to as type Vc. With these lesions, arteries are variously narrowed, generally more than with type IV. Importantly, as with type IV lesions, type V lesions may develop fissures, hematoma, and/or thrombus (type VI lesion), and for this reason too they are clinically relevant.
Loose and sagging skin of the fingers.
Retinopathy which extends from the center of the optic disc to twice the distance from the center of the optic disc to the center of the macula.
The presence of an abnormal membrane obstructing the urethra.
The presence of a fistula connecting the urinary bladder to the vagina.
The foreskin becomes trapped behind the glans penis, and cannot be pulled back to its normal flaccid position covering the glans penis.
A focal cognitive seizure with dyscalculia / acalculia characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

Complete absence of the dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, that is, absence of the inner and the outer dynein arms, which normally are situated inside and outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
Pathological protein aggregates formed by hyperphosphorylation of a microtubule-associated protein known as tau, causing it to aggregate in an insoluble form.
An abnormality of the shape of the lumbar vertebra L2 such that it is wedge-shaped (narrow towards the front).
EEG showing diffuse slowing without interruption.
Intracellular aggregates of actin and actin-associated proteins within nerve cells.

Type III (intermediate) atherosclerotic lesions are the morphological and chemical bridge between type II and advanced lesions. Type III lesions appear in some adaptive intimal thickenings (progression-prone locations) in young adults and are characterized by pools of extracellular lipid in addition to all the components of type II lesions.
Agenesis of one or more vertebrae of the cervical vertebral column.
An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eyelid movements or their control.
A focal cognitive seizure with memory impairment characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.
Intermittent episodes of paralysis of all four limbs.
Increased amount of pigmentation in the macula lutea.

A subtype of retinitis pigmentosa in which, instead of the pathology starting in the mid-periphery like typical retinitis pigmentosa, the disease starts in the near periphery closer to the vascular arcades and tends to spare the far periphery.
Increase in size of the folds of skin between the outer labia.

A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the aortic origin. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
A cataract that affects the posterior part of the cortex of the lens.
Blockage of urine flow from the renal pelvis to the proximal ureter.
Inflammation of the synovial membrane of the sacroiliac joint.
Focal emotional seizure with crying in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
Epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Any deviation from the normal concentration of the HDL3a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3a particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.2-8.79 nm.
A seizure characterized by a sensation in the head such as light-headedness or headache.
A condition in which the superior portion of the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal.
A fracture of the thoracic vertebra that is caused by a loss of bone mass (osteoporosis) that occurs as part of aging.
Unusual prominence of the median palatal raphe, which is the ridge formed by the fusion of the two plates of the skull that form the hard palate.
Focal emotional seizure with crying (dacrystic)in which awareness is retained throughout.
A focal autonomic seizure with pupillary dilation / constriction characterized by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.
Aphasic status epilepticus is a type of focal non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma characterized by a cognitive (rather than motor) language deficit.
Loss of the superficial layer of the oral mucosa usually resulting in a shallow or crusted lesion.
Aplasia, that is failure to develop, of the fallopian tube.
Congenital anomaly characterized by closure or failure to develop an opening in the urethra in females.
A focal cognitive seizure with dysgraphia / agraphia characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.
A failure to collect oocytes after an apparently normal controlled ovarian hyperstimulation cycle for in vitro fertilization.
A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp in the parietal area.
Avascular cystic elevations of the superior conjunctiva not related to ocular surgery or trauma.

A highly malignant embryonal tumor of infancy and young childhood characterized by neuroectodermal elements organized in distinctive multilayered rosettes. Ependymoblastomas are large lesions that occur in the supratentorial compartment, typically displaying a physical connection to the ventricular system.

Any deviation from a count of antral follicles that is normal for age. Antral follicles appear as small fluid-filled sacs that contain an immature egg. Antral follicle count can be measured (usually on day 2-5 of the menstrual cycle) by transvaginal ultrasound. The number of antral follicles may reflect ovarian reserve.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the calcaneus.
